Wash and dry produce.

Drain @mango{4%ounce}, reserving juice in a #small bowl{}; roughly chop mango. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}; mince a few slices until you have 2 TBSP (4 TBSP for 4 servings). Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Quarter @lime{1}. Halve, core, and thinly slice @long green pepper{1} into strips.

In a second small bowl, combine mango, minced onion, half the cilantro, and a squeeze of lime juice. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion and green pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned and slightly softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Reduce to medium heat.

Add @ground beef{10%ounce} and @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp} to pan with veggies; season with salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

Stir in mango juice and @Tex-Mex Paste{1}; cook until thickened and saucy, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Remove pan from heat and stir in remaining cilantro.

> Open package of chicken and drain off any excess liquid. Swap in chicken or beef for pork. (No need to break up chicken into pieces!)

While pork cooks, wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates and fill with pork filling. Top with mango salsa and dollop with @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> The magic ingredient that makes these quick one-pan pork tacos sing is a speedy homemade mango salsa that adds tangy-juicy-tropical goodness to every tasty bite.